@node requirements "requirements"

Circuit requires:

@{fg shine}*@{fg text} An Amiga

@{fg shine}*@{fg text} Mui V3.x or more.

@{fg shine}*@{fg text} You can @{u}execute@{uu} circuit on a sloow 68000, but it doesn't mean it will be useable... I use a 68040 @ 25MHz, which is fast enough.

@{fg shine}*@{fg text} Kickstart 3.x, my program uses the datatypes to load the images and ObtainBestPen() to choose the colours. If you don't have it, just get it!

@{fg shine}*@{fg text} All images of circuit are done in 256 colour; and these 256 colours are allocated during startup. So it is better to have lots of colours..
@endnode
@node "Installation" "How to put Circuit on your hard drive"
This is rather simple, just copy all files in a directory of your hard disk.

Note that the current directory must be the one were circuit is installed when you run it. So if you try to run it using the 'execute command' function of your workbench, it won't work.
@endnode
@node window "Main window"

The main window consists of three lists:

@{b}THE CIRCUIT FUNCTIONS@{ub} (named Circuit)

The first icon, 'bind', is used to bind objects: Select an output of an object in a project window and then an input of another object.
A single output can be linked to several inputs but only one output can be linked to a single input

The second icon, 'load', is used to load a circuit from disk. An asl requester is then opened. Select a circuit to load it. A new project window is opened for that circuit.

The third icon, 'save', is used to save a circuit to disk. The circuit represented in the last selected project window will be saved. (If you are not sure, select a project window and then this icon). It is unavailable if the last selected window has been closed.
The size and position of the window is also saved.

The fourth icon, 'new', is used to start a new circuit, it opens an empty project window.

The last icon open a preference window where you can set the colour of the wires and the selection. (See @{"Project windows" link project} for more information about selection.
These preferences aren't yet useful because they can't be saved.

@{b}THE MACRO LIST@{ub} (named List)

It contains all macros the program has found in the 'macros' directory.
You can create a new object if you drag one of these icons into a @{"project window" link project}.
Note that because of a bug of circuit, the topleft corner of the object will be under the pointer.
If anyone can tell me how to get the 'real' position of the object being drop, tell it to me!

@{b}THE MACRO FUNCTIONS@{ub} (named Macro)

This list is used to create a new macro. See @{"macro creation" link macro} for more information about creating a macro.

@endnode
@node project "Project windows"

The project windows are the windows were you create circuits. You can have as many opened project windows at a time as you want.

To create an object, choose it in the macro list ('List'), drag and drop it were you want.

You can of course move objects if you drag one and move it somewere else in the window.
Note: here is the same bug than the drop: the topleft corner will not be where you see it just before you drop the object but under the mouse pointer.
drag drop between project window is not yet supported.

Circuit has a feature that allows you to select several objects at a time and act on all these objects directely: draw a rectangle (click on a the top left corner, let the mouse button pressed, move the mouse to the bottom right corner and release the button.
You can now move all these objects if you click in the rectangle and move it,
and, if you resize that rectangle (click somewere near the frame and mouve the mouse), all objects move to fit in the new rectangle.
If you press Del, all objects contained in the rectangle will be deleted.

@endnode
@node macro "Macro creation"

If you want to create a macro:
1) Create the logic circuit representing what you want to do.

2) Select the first icon of the 'Macro' list (inputs)

3) Select the objects that will represent the inputs of the macro.
All these input have to be switches. Note: if you made a mistake, select again a switch you don't want to be an input.

4) If you want to have an input on the macro (that will be changeable by the user, clicking on the macro, like the switches), select the second icon of the 'Macro' list and select the switch you want to be put on your macro.

5) Select the third icon of the 'Macro' list (outputs)

6) Select the objects you want to be the outputs of your macro. If you select an object that has an output on it (e.g. a light), this output will be used, otherwise it will be the first one (topmost)

7) If you want to have an output on your macro (like a light), select the fourth icon and the object you want to be an output on your macro.

8) Click on the last icon of the 'Macro' list (save) to create the macro. The computer asks you the required images.
Important notes: due to a bug of Circuit (I do not know how to read the palette of a picture), you @{u}have to@{uu} have the same palette than the other pictures of the 'Images' directory.
The size of a macro is currently fixed to 28*28 pixels.
Afterwards you can now either select a name in the requester (in this case, the macro will be saved under the name you selected, note that it has to be in the 'Macros' directory so that circuit loads it automatically on startup)
or cancel the requester. In this case the program will create a macro but not save it.

Notes:
The macro definition contains all possible outputs depending of the inputs.
This has advantages and disadvantages:
- you can do a circuit with as many objects as you want, it will change neither the speed of calculation nor the size of the file
- when you put too much inputs, the file size, loading time and memory usage will increase a lot:
with no input (constant objects?), there is only one possible output.
with three inputs, there will be eight possible outputs, this is ok.
with eight inputs, there will be two hundred and fifty-six possible outputs, which becomes really too large.
the maximum is fixed to ten inputs and ten outputs (including those on the macro), but you should never create so many inputs, because the macro definition will contain the 1024 different states!

But the number of outputs doesn't matter.

When deciding so, I thought that the really big advantage was the most important: a macro to add binary values is as fast to calculate than a 'NAND' macro.
@endnode
@node Past "The history of Circuit"

While I was doing a physics work at school (a study of logic circuits), my physics teacher suggested me to write a computer program related to logic circuits.
So I started writing a small and rather limited program, that opened on a fixed screen mode (pal 320×256), there were only the switches, the lights and some basic doors (NAND,AND,OR,XOR) available.
All these objects were drawn with some lines, because I did not know how to display a brush at a any place of the screen (I still do not know it, anyway :).
I later decided to do the macros, so I rewrote the program to read the macros from disk. The images were still done with simple lines.

Thinking that those vector objects were really ugly, I decided to use MUI, because it was easier to display pictures with it.
So I threw out Circuit and started again to write it using MUI. The first version was stuck to one project window and was of course full of bugs.
I then managed to put all variables related to that precise window in the userdata of the class, so it was easy then to allow opening/closing as many window as wanted.
Next thing implemented was the creation of macros directely from the program and ability to load/save circuits on disk.
I then started to write the selection of several objects at a time and preferences window.

later history:

Version 1.1 (09/04/98)
· Objects can be deleted using the Del key. select some objects and then press Del.
· Spent my holidays debugging :( and removed some bugs :)
@endnode
@node bugs "Arrgh, will I once get rid of 'em??"

 ! Some memory is lost everytime circuit is ran.

 ! The palette is set within the program, all picture @{u}have@{uu} to be done with the @{u}same@{uu} palette.

 ! The size of every picture displayed (icons and objects) is fixed to 28×28 (because I do not really know how to get the size of a super_picture object and it is a bit complicated to write).

I you either find the cause of one of these bugs or find another bug (What? Don't I have enough?), don't hesitate to mail me :-)
(I don't want any bug to hide in my code ;)

 ! Position problems. See about the @{"tools window" link window} for more information.
@endnode
@node future "What I have to do..."
 - Of course eradicate those @{"Bugs" link bugs} out of my program.

 - Let the user save the preferences, they are quite useless without this feature..

 - let the user set where a wire have to go:


        []·                      []·        (because a circuit can look somehow
           \\                       | ·-·     cluttered when there are lot of wires
instead of  \\     , he could do:   ·/ /      everywhere, look the multiplier circuit
             \\                       /       for example)
              ·[]                    ·--[]

I thing about doing a 'relai' OBJECT:
To draw the wire, there will be: a link to the last point and each point will have a pointer to the previous one or NIL if it is the first.
It should be like this:

OBJECT relai
    x,y -> position, between zero and one thousand, like the other.
    previous:PTR TO relai
ENDOBJECT

 - Put in the definition of a macro at which position are the inputs/outputs.

If you think you're able to do one of these things, don't hesitate to mail me. (Contact me before trying to change the program
(So that I can send you the latest version and to check there aren't several people working on the same thing)
You can also contact me if you've another idea.
@endnode
